{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 15:20:09.733292", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report\\nTarget: SDN spine–leaf lab (hosts in 10.0.0.0/24, management 20.0.0.0/24, OVS switches leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1; controller tcp:20.0.0.100:6633)\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Control plane appears up: each OVS bridge reports a Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" and shows \"is_connected: true\".\\n- Data plane (host-to-host L2 forwarding) is broken: pings between hosts time out; hosts in the same 10.0.0.0/24 cannot reach each other.\\n- Root cause localization: the internal/local bridge interfaces (the OVS \"LOCAL\" ports / bridge device) on the switches are DOWN (PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN). This leaves the OVS datapath without an active local interface and prevents host L2 connectivity across the bridges.\\n- Secondary observation: systemctl reports openvswitch-switch as \"inactive (dead)\", while ovsdb-server and ovs-vswitchd processes are actually running — a mismatch that may be relevant to service lifecycle/configuration but is not the immediate cause of the observed loss of host connectivity.\\n\\nObserved abnormal behavior\\n1. Host-level connectivity failure\\n   - Ping tests from host_1_1 to host_2_1 and between host_1_1 and host_1_2 timed out (no ICMP replies).\\n   - get_reachability summary returned many \"unknown\" statuses for host-to-host reachability.\\n\\n2. OVS bridge/local interfaces down\\n   - ovs-ofctl show output for leaf_1 and leaf_2 shows the LOCAL interface with:\\n     - leaf_1: \"LOCAL(leaf_1): ... config: PORT_DOWN  state: LINK_DOWN\"\\n     - leaf_2: \"LOCAL(leaf_2): ... config: PORT_DOWN  state: LINK_DOWN\"\\n   - ip link shows the bridge device (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) state DOWN:\\n     - e.g. \"3: leaf_1: <BROADCAST,MULTICAST> ... state DOWN\"\\n   - ovs-system device is shown as DOWN (ip -d link show ovs-system: state DOWN).\\n\\n3. Open vSwitch service state mismatch\\n   - systemctl status openvswitch-switch reports \"Active: inactive (dead)\" on leaf_1, leaf_2 and spine_1.\\n   - However ps aux shows ovsdb-server and ovs-vswitchd processes running on the switches, and ovs-vsctl / ovs-ofctl can query bridge state — indicating the OVS daemons are running despite systemctl reporting the service inactive.\\n\\nSupporting evidence (selected outputs)\\n- Ping attempt timed out:\\n  - ping from host_1_1 to 10.0.0.5 timed out (command exceeded timeout).\\n- OVS local port state (leaf_1):\\n  - \"LOCAL(leaf_1): addr:5e:6a:09:4f:36:4d\\n       config:     PORT_DOWN\\n       state:      LINK_DOWN\"\\n- Bridge device down:\\n  - \"3: leaf_1: <BROADCAST,MULTICAST> mtu 1500 qdisc noop state DOWN\"\\n- ovs-system link:\\n  - \"2: ovs-system: <BROADCAST,MULTICAST> ... state DOWN\"\\n- Controller connected:\\n  - Bridge description includes: Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" is_connected: true\\n- systemctl vs processes:\\n  - systemctl: \"Active: inactive (dead)\" for openvswitch-switch\\n  - ps: ovsdb-server and ovs-vswitchd processes are present and running\\n\\nLocalization — faulty/affected devices and components\\n- Affected devices: leaf_1, leaf_2, and spine_1 (all OVS switches in the topology).\\n- Affected components on those devices:\\n  - The OVS bridge device\\'s LOCAL/internal port (the bridge internal interface) is LINK_DOWN / PORT_DOWN.\\n  - The ovs-system virtual interface is DOWN.\\n- Symptoms are present on multiple switches, so the issue is not isolated to a single leaf — the common element is the bridge local/internal interfaces on the OVS switches.\\n\\nRoot-cause analysis (most likely)\\n- Immediate root cause: The OVS bridge internal (LOCAL) interfaces are DOWN (PORT_DOWN/LINK_DOWN). When the LOCAL port / bridge device is down, the kernel datapath is not presenting an active internal interface for local host attachment/forwarding; as a result, host interfaces attached to the bridges cannot exchange L2 frames through the switch. This explains the host-to-host ping failures despite hosts having correct IPs.\\n- Contributing/related observations:\\n  - The management/control plane is functional: the OVS daemons are running and the bridges show the controller connected. That indicates the control channel (to the SDN controller) is not the reason for data-plane failure.\\n  - The systemctl \"inactive\" status while processes run indicates a mismatch between the init service state and the running daemons (service unit not reflecting actual process state). This could indicate service lifecycle/configuration issues (e.g., OVS started manually, service crashed but daemons restarted by something else, or unit file mismatch). While this doesn\\'t directly cause the LOCAL ports to be down in all switches, it is a noteworthy anomaly that may be related to misconfiguration or an incomplete startup sequence that left internal bridge ports down.\\n- Possible low-level reasons for LOCAL/bridge DOWN (diagnostic hypotheses; not remediation):\\n  - The internal bridge device may have been administratively set DOWN (e.g., ip link set <bridge> down) or created without setting its state UP.\\n  - A kernel datapath/OVS datapath issue that left LOCAL ports unbound/disabled (e.g., mismatch between userspace and kernel datapath).\\n  - A lifecycle/startup issue where OVS daemons were started but the internal bridge interfaces were not brought up or were failed during creation.\\n  - A mis-applied configuration / script that intentionally put LOCAL ports down (less likely given controller connected).\\n\\nOther observations\\n- Host interface configurations are correct (10.0.0.x/24) and show RX counters, but pings still fail — consistent with hosts not being bridged at L2 to each other.\\n- Management addresses on switches (20.0.0.x) exist and show heavy RX/TX counters on the management interfaces (eth6 on leafs, eth4 on spine), consistent with control/management traffic being active while data-plane is not forwarding host L2 traffic.\\n\\nSuggested next diagnostic checks (if you want to continue investigation)\\n- Check kernel OVS datapath status (dmesg / ovs-dpctl) and the state of the internal ports at the kernel level.\\n- Check if the internal bridge interfaces are administratively down (ip link show; ip link set <bridge> up would normally bring them up).\\n- Inspect OVS logs (/var/log/openvswitch/) for errors related to creating or bringing up the LOCAL port or datapath errors.\\n- Reconcile systemctl service state vs running daemons to determine why the unit is \"inactive\" while processes run.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Network control plane (controller connectivity and OVS daemons) appears up, but data plane is down.\\n- Root cause for host connectivity loss: OVS bridge internal (LOCAL) interfaces on leaf_1, leaf_2, and spine_1 are DOWN (PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN), causing L2 forwarding failure between hosts.\\n- There is also an anomalous mismatch between systemctl service state and running OVS processes which is worth investigating further, but the immediate cause of host reachability loss is the DOWN state of the bridge/local interfaces.\\n\\nIf you want, I can run the suggested follow-up checks (logs, ovs-dpctl, ip link manipulations, or more targeted ping/traceroute tests) to gather further evidence. (I will not apply any configuration changes unless you explicitly ask for remediation.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='caba44fb-2283-4bff-a25c-0c472e7e1155'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
